The `string.concat()` method in JavaScript is used to concatenate multiple strings together. It takes one or more strings as arguments and returns a new string that is the result of joining them together.

Here is an example:

```javascript
const string1 = 'Hello';
const string2 = 'World';

const concatenatedString = string1.concat(' ', string2); // "Hello World"

console.log(concatenatedString);
```

In this example, the `concat()` method is used to join `string1` and `string2` together, with a space in between, resulting in the string `"Hello World"`.

Yes, you can use the `+` operator for string concatenation instead of the `concat()` method. In your example, you can concatenate `string1` and `string2` with a space in between like this:

```javascript
const string1 = 'Hello';
const string2 = 'World';

const concatenatedString = string1 + ' ' + string2; // "Hello World"

console.log(concatenatedString);
```

Both `concat()` method and `+` operator serve the same purpose of concatenating strings. It's a matter of personal preference which one to use.

To get the value of the selected input element, you can use the `value` property of the element. Here's how you can do it with the `document.querySelector()` method:

```javascript
const inputElement = document.querySelector('input[value="SMS"]');
const value = inputElement.value;
console.log(value);
```

In this example, the selected input element is assigned to the `inputElement` variable using `document.querySelector('input[value="SMS"]')`. Then, the `value` property is accessed to retrieve the value of the input element. Finally, the value is printed to the console using `console.log()`.
